00:53:43.670 --> 00:53:45.590
That would be the speed
at which something

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:47.340
would have to cross
the wing given

00:53:47.340 --> 00:53:49.880
the precision of the timing
on those experiments.

00:53:49.880 --> 00:53:52.027
I mean, you can
synchronize them with,

00:53:52.027 --> 00:53:54.110
certainly with picoseconds
or something like that,

00:53:54.110 --> 00:53:55.950
but I don't know what
the detail would be.

00:53:55.950 --> 00:53:58.470
And then you can, another fun
thing you can do is you can,

00:53:58.470 --> 00:54:01.590
because the Earth is rotating,
you can actually watch

00:54:01.590 --> 00:54:04.640
the experiment for a 24-hour
period and if universe has any

00:54:04.640 --> 00:54:07.800
kind of hypothetical frame of
reference that's an absolute

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:10.280
frame of reference, you would
rotate through that frame,

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:14.030
so you should see variations
in the timing, which you don't.

00:54:14.030 --> 00:54:16.290
So the whole thing
seems to be kosher

00:54:16.290 --> 00:54:18.265
as far as Einstein's
theory is concerned.

00:54:18.265 --> 00:54:19.140
AUDIENCE: OK, thanks.

00:54:19.140 --> 00:54:20.134
GEORGE MUSSER: Sure.

00:54:20.134 --> 00:54:22.050
It's actually fun to get
into the nitty gritty

00:54:22.050 --> 00:54:22.925
of these experiments.

00:54:22.925 --> 00:54:25.240
The timing is a huge issue.

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:28.140
Those crystals are actually
extremely inefficient.

00:54:28.140 --> 00:54:33.250
They'll release only like
one laser photon in a billion

00:54:33.250 --> 00:54:36.310
will actually produce
the entangled photon.

00:54:36.310 --> 00:54:38.890
So there's a lot of statistics
that you have to work through

00:54:38.890 --> 00:54:41.220
on that and that's why this
has taken decades really

00:54:41.220 --> 00:54:43.246
to bring to it's current state.

00:54:46.340 --> 00:54:49.934
AUDIENCE: You skipped over some
slides about holographic theory

00:54:49.934 --> 00:54:51.600
and how it relates
to black holes, which

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:52.790
is an idea I've
learned about recently

00:54:52.790 --> 00:54:53.840
and it's really compelling.

00:54:53.840 --> 00:54:55.881
So I wondering if you
could elaborate on how that

00:54:55.881 --> 00:54:58.300
might relate to non-locality.

00:54:58.300 --> 00:55:02.352
GEORGE MUSSER: Yes, so, this
might be too long for an answer

00:55:02.352 --> 00:55:03.060
to your question.

00:55:03.060 --> 00:55:04.809
We can talk about it
more in the corridor.

00:55:04.809 --> 00:55:07.990
But it goes back to what I
was saying about black holes

00:55:07.990 --> 00:55:09.590
being like incinerators.

00:55:09.590 --> 00:55:13.230
They have a temperature to them.

00:55:13.230 --> 00:55:16.160
That comes out of the
work of Stephen Hawking.

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:18.774
So, first of all,
that immediately

00:55:18.774 --> 00:55:20.440
implies, by the way,
that the black hole

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:22.390
must consist of some kind
of microscopic structure.

00:55:22.390 --> 00:55:24.640
Anything that has a temperature
and can raise or lower

00:55:24.640 --> 00:55:27.700
temperature, like water,
has to be molecular

00:55:27.700 --> 00:55:29.450
because the molecular
motions are what's

00:55:29.450 --> 00:55:30.620
actually storing the heat.

00:55:30.620 --> 00:55:32.170
It's what's actually
representing the concept

00:55:32.170 --> 00:55:32.860
of temperature here.

00:55:32.860 --> 00:55:34.359
So the black hole
already, you know,

00:55:34.359 --> 00:55:38.440
has to be divisible into some
kind of molecular, atomic,

00:55:38.440 --> 00:55:40.134
or microscopic structure.

00:55:40.134 --> 00:55:41.550
And then you can
play other games.

00:55:41.550 --> 00:55:43.650
You can do things like
hypothetical games of,

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:47.469
well, if I add a certain
amount of energy to-- well,

00:55:47.469 --> 00:55:48.510
let's take it with water.

00:55:48.510 --> 00:55:50.176
If I add a certain
amount of heat energy

00:55:50.176 --> 00:55:52.800
to this water and the
temperature bumps up

00:55:52.800 --> 00:55:55.590
just a teeny amount,
then I know there

00:55:55.590 --> 00:55:58.020
must be a lot of molecules
because the energy's being

00:55:58.020 --> 00:55:59.549
divided over those molecules.

00:55:59.549 --> 00:56:01.340
If it goes up a huge
amount, few molecules.

00:56:01.340 --> 00:56:02.230
You can actually
count the number

00:56:02.230 --> 00:56:04.000
of molecules in the
water, and you can

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:05.860
do the same for black holes.

00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:08.860
And with water, when you do a
counting exercise like that,

00:56:08.860 --> 00:56:11.390
the number of molecules is
proportional to the volume

00:56:11.390 --> 00:56:11.890
of water.

00:56:11.890 --> 00:56:14.130
If I have a bigger
bottle, more molecules.

00:56:14.130 --> 00:56:15.090
It just scales up.

00:56:15.090 --> 00:56:17.324
There's a volumetric scaling.

00:56:17.324 --> 00:56:19.240
It's too long to go back
to the slide on this,

00:56:19.240 --> 00:56:21.480
but if you do the same
thing for black holes,

00:56:21.480 --> 00:56:23.940
it scales up with the
area of the black hole.

00:56:23.940 --> 00:56:27.050
If you do this kind of
exercise of how many molecules

00:56:27.050 --> 00:56:28.750
does the black hole have?

00:56:28.750 --> 00:56:31.260
It's proportional to the
surface area of the black hole,

00:56:31.260 --> 00:56:34.040
not to the interior volume.

00:56:34.040 --> 00:56:37.930
So a black hole from the
outside looks three-dimensional

00:56:37.930 --> 00:56:41.610
but it's acting, it's behaving
as a two-dimensional system.

00:56:41.610 --> 00:56:43.300
And that is where
the word hologram

00:56:43.300 --> 00:56:44.760
enters this whole discussion.

00:56:44.760 --> 00:56:47.900
Because a hologram, you
know, Princess Leia,

00:56:47.900 --> 00:56:49.640
looks three-dimensional.

00:56:49.640 --> 00:56:53.290
You can actually walk around the
droid projecting Princess Leia

00:56:53.290 --> 00:56:55.600
and see it looks
three-dimensional,

00:56:55.600 --> 00:56:58.040
but you know that it's
two-dimensional, ultimately

00:56:58.040 --> 00:56:58.150
two-dimensional.

00:56:58.150 --> 00:56:59.900
And you could probably
get that by looking

00:56:59.900 --> 00:57:02.235
at the kind of details
that Princess Leia had.

00:57:02.235 --> 00:57:04.236
If you enlarged
the hologram, you'd

00:57:04.236 --> 00:57:05.860
begin to see some
graininess in it that

00:57:05.860 --> 00:57:07.710
would indicate the
thing is actually

00:57:07.710 --> 00:57:10.135
a two-dimensional projection.

00:57:10.135 --> 00:57:11.635
AUDIENCE: But isn't
the surface area

00:57:11.635 --> 00:57:16.080
of the black hole related to
its volume, like a sphere.

00:57:16.080 --> 00:57:18.100
GEORGE MUSSER: You would
think so but that, no.

00:57:22.840 --> 00:57:26.380
I mean, there's a couple levels
at which the answer is no.

00:57:26.380 --> 00:57:29.240
First, the level
is actually-- even

00:57:29.240 --> 00:57:31.810
in general relativity theory,
the interior of a black hole

00:57:31.810 --> 00:57:34.420
is a highly distorted spacetime.

00:57:34.420 --> 00:57:35.920
So it doesn't scale up.

00:57:35.920 --> 00:57:38.211
There's actually more space
in it than there should be,

00:57:38.211 --> 00:57:39.917
in a way, because
of this distortion.

00:57:39.917 --> 00:57:41.500
So it looks like a
ball on the outside

00:57:41.500 --> 00:57:43.987
but you can't do your
4/3 pi r cubed with it.

00:57:43.987 --> 00:57:45.070
It doesn't work like that.

00:57:45.070 --> 00:57:48.020
And worse, in the quantum
theory of gravity, at least

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:50.560
according to some of
these interpretations,

00:57:50.560 --> 00:57:52.040
there is no interior.

00:57:52.040 --> 00:57:53.310
So there's nothing to volume.

00:57:53.310 --> 00:57:55.764
There's no volume there at all.

00:57:55.764 --> 00:57:57.430
And, oh, but the
connection to locality,

00:57:57.430 --> 00:57:58.660
I promised to go back.

00:57:58.660 --> 00:58:02.990
The volumetric scaling is
actually related to locality.

00:58:02.990 --> 00:58:07.782
So if you scale up--
if I have two water

00:58:07.782 --> 00:58:09.740
molecules-- molecules,
certainly, but certainly

00:58:09.740 --> 00:58:13.890
bottles, I can treat each
independently and then

00:58:13.890 --> 00:58:16.190
add up the total
volume because I've

00:58:16.190 --> 00:58:20.844
divided the bucket of water, or
whatever I have into subvolumes

00:58:20.844 --> 00:58:23.010
and added up the subvolumes
to get the total volume.

00:58:23.010 --> 00:58:25.090
That's where you get
the volumetric scaling.

00:58:25.090 --> 00:58:29.490
You just integrate
over that x cubed.

00:58:29.490 --> 00:58:34.889
So that volumetric scaling
is failing for black holes

00:58:34.889 --> 00:58:37.180
and since the volumetric
scaling comes out of locality,

00:58:37.180 --> 00:58:39.180
it means locality is
failing for black holes.

00:58:39.180 --> 00:58:40.638
A lot of these
black hole arguments

00:58:40.638 --> 00:58:43.587
require a couple
stages in logic.

00:58:43.587 --> 00:58:44.295
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:58:44.295 --> 00:58:45.128
GEORGE MUSSER: Sure.

00:58:47.640 --> 00:58:50.470
So you guys are all like happy
with all this and there no

00:58:50.470 --> 00:58:52.440
questions?

00:58:52.440 --> 00:58:54.080
It takes time to
