00:58:57.116 --> 00:58:58.740
AUDIENCE: Hi, I just
have one question.

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:01.140
I don't understand--
well, by some definition

00:59:01.140 --> 00:59:03.470
of understanding-- the
part about when you're

00:59:03.470 --> 00:59:05.406
saying that the black
hole is irreversible,

00:59:05.406 --> 00:59:08.240
you're saying that you would
expect it to be reversible

00:59:08.240 --> 00:59:10.120
but it's not what.

00:59:10.120 --> 00:59:11.880
You would expect
it based on what?

00:59:11.880 --> 00:59:13.624
Based on the way
the math works out?

00:59:13.624 --> 00:59:14.415
GEORGE MUSSER: Yes.

00:59:14.415 --> 00:59:17.140
AUDIENCE: And the other
one based on observation?

00:59:17.140 --> 00:59:18.050
It's not clear.

00:59:18.050 --> 00:59:18.900
GEORGE MUSSER: I
rushed through that

00:59:18.900 --> 00:59:20.275
and I'm glad you
called me on it.

00:59:20.275 --> 00:59:25.280
So the question is, in
general relativity theory

00:59:25.280 --> 00:59:29.200
black holes are
irreversible by definition.

00:59:29.200 --> 00:59:30.700
You fall in, you
can't get back out.

00:59:30.700 --> 00:59:33.120
It's all the well known
properties of black holes.

00:59:33.120 --> 00:59:34.745
You'd have to exceed
the speed of light

00:59:34.745 --> 00:59:35.850
to get out, specifically.

00:59:35.850 --> 00:59:41.840
So that has always been
considered a paradox in a way.

00:59:41.840 --> 00:59:44.740
It's always been considered
a problem that black holes

00:59:44.740 --> 00:59:50.010
seemed to be irreversible when
everything else in science is--

00:59:50.010 --> 00:59:51.720
AUDIENCE: And by
seem to be, you mean

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:54.310
seem according to the math?

00:59:54.310 --> 00:59:55.500
GEORGE MUSSER: Yes, yes.

00:59:55.500 --> 01:00:00.450
Well, certainly
according to the theory.

01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:03.960
They're observationally
irreversible.

01:00:03.960 --> 01:00:05.520
What's a good example of that?

01:00:05.520 --> 01:00:09.124
I mean, the simple example
would-- it's not entirely

01:00:09.124 --> 01:00:11.790
the same as the theoretical one,
but I'll give it to you anyway.

01:00:11.790 --> 01:00:15.430
So if you have a neutron star,
just any physical object,

01:00:15.430 --> 01:00:20.070
and matter falls onto that
object, it will heat it up.

01:00:20.070 --> 01:00:22.600
It's like, if you pummel
it, it will heat up

01:00:22.600 --> 01:00:25.970
and the object will
radiate away that energy.

01:00:25.970 --> 01:00:27.980
So there's a steady state
that will be achieved

01:00:27.980 --> 01:00:29.550
in any kind of material system.

01:00:29.550 --> 01:00:32.370
And this is a well
known aspect of stars

01:00:32.370 --> 01:00:34.725
and other systems like this.

01:00:34.725 --> 01:00:36.100
Black holes are
unable to achieve

01:00:36.100 --> 01:00:37.933
any kind of steady state
like that, at least

01:00:37.933 --> 01:00:40.500
according to the theory and
also according to observations.

01:00:40.500 --> 01:00:42.700
You see, in the
example I showed,

01:00:42.700 --> 01:00:45.830
the black hole was actually
sucking in some gas but it

01:00:45.830 --> 01:00:51.107
wasn't-- as it sucked in, it
didn't heat up and release

01:00:51.107 --> 01:00:52.440
the energy of the gas out again.

01:00:52.440 --> 01:00:54.360
So there seemed to
be an irreversibility

01:00:54.360 --> 01:00:55.600
in that process.

01:00:55.600 --> 01:00:57.250
So the contention
that Hawking made

01:00:57.250 --> 01:01:00.770
is that if you look long
enough, as in 10 to the 30 year

01:01:00.770 --> 01:01:02.460
long enough, you
would eventually

01:01:02.460 --> 01:01:06.100
see the energy emerge back out
in the form of these Hawking

01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:07.840
particles.

01:01:07.840 --> 01:01:12.580
And that also was irreversible
because the Hawking particles

01:01:12.580 --> 01:01:13.910
coming out are random.

01:01:13.910 --> 01:01:15.342
You couldn't unwind the system.

01:01:15.342 --> 01:01:17.050
AUDIENCE: Did that
correlate [INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:17.050 --> 01:01:19.205
GEORGE MUSSER: Exactly
there's no correlation.

01:01:19.205 --> 01:01:21.580
In fact, I'm glad you bring
up the word correlation there

01:01:21.580 --> 01:01:24.270
because if you had two
entangled, if you played

01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:25.960
a game, two entangled
particles, you

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:27.199
threw one into a black hole.

01:01:27.199 --> 01:01:28.740
The one that came
out would no longer

01:01:28.740 --> 01:01:32.270
be entangled with that
one that you kept,

01:01:32.270 --> 01:01:37.711
which is violating the
reversibility of quantum

01:01:37.711 --> 01:01:38.210
theory.

01:01:38.210 --> 01:01:40.520
That's actually why
it's called a paradox.

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:42.830
Because quantum
theory is telling you

01:01:42.830 --> 01:01:44.620
that you have an
irreversible process,

01:01:44.620 --> 01:01:46.350
which is against quantum theory.

01:01:46.350 --> 01:01:50.899
So there's a loop there
that is contradictory.

01:01:50.899 --> 01:01:51.690
Does that help any?

01:01:51.690 --> 01:01:54.250
I know it's hard to get
your mind around but--

01:01:54.250 --> 01:01:55.210
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

01:01:55.210 --> 01:01:56.170
GEORGE MUSSER: Sure.

